1 Introduction
1.1 Background and Motivation
Car pricing in Tunisia often lacks transparency,
leading sellers to misjudge their car‚Äôs value and
buyers to risk overpaying. To reduce mispricing and
improve trust in the market, a data-driven system is
needed to analyze historical car data and predict
fair prices based on a vehicle‚Äôs features.
1.2 Problem Statement
There is no clear or consistent method to evaluate car
prices especially in Tunisia and generally worldwide.
1.3 Research Objectives
‚Ä¢ Analyze car market behavior and pricing trends in
Tunisia.
‚Ä¢ Identify key relationships and patterns within
multivariate car data.
‚Ä¢ Segment cars and buyer types using clustering
techniques.
‚Ä¢ Reduce data complexity to extract the main latent
factors affecting price.
‚Ä¢ Discover associations between car features and their
impact on pricing.
1.4 Research Questions
Are cars in the Tunisian market generally overpriced by
sellers?
What is the fair market value of a given car based on
its features?
